prompt:
I run the service side of a bike workshop and our end-of-week numbers are currently a spreadsheet ritual. I want the calculations in code so the till app can show them live. C++20, stdlib only, two new files: report.hpp and report.cpp.

The record type and the five report functions, exactly:

    struct WorkOrder {
        std::string id;        // "WO-1041"
        std::string mechanic;  // who has the wrench
        std::string category;  // "brakes", "drivetrain", "wheels", ...
        int minutes;           // labor booked on the order
        long parts_cents;      // parts charged to the order
        bool closed;           // finished and billed?
    };

    long shop_revenue_cents(const std::vector<WorkOrder>& orders,
                            long rate_cents_per_hour);
    std::map<std::string, long> revenue_by_mechanic(
            const std::vector<WorkOrder>& orders, long rate_cents_per_hour);
    std::vector<std::string> backlog_ids(const std::vector<WorkOrder>& orders);

    struct PartsSplit {
        std::vector<std::string> heavy;
        std::vector<std::string> light;
    };
    PartsSplit split_by_parts(const std::vector<WorkOrder>& orders,
                              long threshold_cents);
    std::string busiest_category(const std::vector<WorkOrder>& orders);

Business rules — these are exactly where the spreadsheet kept going wrong, so please follow them to the letter:

- An order bills only once it is closed. Billing for one order = parts_cents + labor, where labor = minutes * rate_cents_per_hour / 60 in integer arithmetic, truncated PER ORDER before anything is summed. Do not total the minutes first; the accountant reconciles per order and the cent has to match.
- shop_revenue_cents sums that over all closed orders. revenue_by_mechanic does the same grouped by mechanic; a mechanic with no closed orders must be absent from the map entirely (an explicit zero entry reads as "worked for free" on the till).
- backlog_ids lists the ids of OPEN orders, most booked minutes first; equal minutes fall back to id ascending. This feeds the whiteboard, order matters.
- split_by_parts looks at closed orders only and splits their ids by parts_cents >= threshold_cents into heavy (at or above) and light (below). Both lists keep the orders' original relative order — the mechanic reads them against the paper pile, which is in arrival order.
- busiest_category totals minutes across ALL orders, open and closed (wrench time is wrench time), and returns the category with the most; ties go to the lexicographically smallest category name; empty input returns "".
- No printing, no globals, no mutation of the input vector. Functions get called with the same data repeatedly and must give identical answers.

Use the standard library properly — this is bread-and-butter <algorithm>/<numeric> material and the reviewers will expect it to read that way, but only the outputs are checked.

`make test` is the acceptance gate; Makefile, mintest.h and test_report.cpp are fixed.
